<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1437,1586,1863]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1766,1791]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Remarks.</emphasis>
A valid species. Found so far only on blue marlin (
<taxonomicName box="[927,1073,1767,1790]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Molidae" genus="Mola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tetraodontiformes" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigricans">
<emphasis box="[927,1073,1767,1790]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">M. nigricans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) in the south Atlantic (
<bibRefCitation author="Hogans" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refString="Hogans, W. E. (1988 c) Pennella makaira new species (Copepoda: Pennellidae) from the Atlantic Blue Marlin (Makira nigricans) in the Caribbean Sea. Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington, 101 (1), 15 - 19." type="journal article" year="1988" yearSuffix="c">Hogans 1988c</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Williams" box="[237,655,1802,1827]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refString="Williams, E. H. &amp; Bunkley-Williams, L. (1996) Parasites of offshore big game fishes of Puerto Rico and the western Atlantic. University of Puerto Rico, Mayaguez, 329 pp." type="book" year="1996">Williams &amp; Bunkley-Williams 1996</bibRefCitation>
). A small species with a unique overall shape and uniform papillae structure between specimens. The only small (&lt;
<quantity box="[686,768,1838,1863]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" unit="mm" value="50.0">50 mm</quantity>
) 
<taxonomicName box="[781,881,1838,1863]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Pennellidae" genus="Pennella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siphonostomatoida" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[781,881,1838,1863]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Pennella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
known to infest large scombriform fishes.
</paragraph>
